  "slug": "guillermo-del-toros-frankenstein-and-the-best-frankenstein-m",
  "title": "Guillermo del Toro’s ‘Frankenstein’ and the Best Frankenstein Movies. Plus: Jennifer Lawrence Is Ablaze in ‘Die My Love.’",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Amanda Dobbins",
    "Rob Mahoney"
  ],
  "published": "2025-11-07",
  "runtimeMin": 81,
  "format": "Guillermo del Toro's Netflix 'Frankenstein,' a tour of the best Frankenstein movies, and Lynne Ramsay's postpartum drama 'Die My Love.'",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The morning's news",
      "note": "two trailers and a Muppet",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Michael",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Antoine Fuqua's Michael Jackson biopic. The hosts pan the trailer as flat and near-AI in its polish; Miles Teller plays Jackson's attorney. A legal fight with the Jackson estate forced a third-act rewrite and a delay out of October, which the hosts blame for the worst box-office October in 25 years."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Testament of Ann Lee",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Mona Fastvold's musical about the Shaker founder, with Amanda Seyfried. Sean and Amanda have seen it: 'not a perfect movie, but a fascinating one,' strongest in its first half."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "Guillermo del Toro's 'Frankenstein'",
      "note": "now on Netflix",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Frankenstein",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Del Toro's 13th feature, from the Mary Shelley novel. Oscar Isaac's Victor plays broad; Jacob Elordi's creature is the emotional center and the part del Toro clearly cares about. All three admire the practical sets, creature design (by Mike Hill), and costumes, but find the film gray, flat, and undercut by weak CGI: 'more interested in the depth of its sets than the depth of its characters.' Split down the middle: Amanda finds the reading facile, Sean lands on admire-not-love, Rob likes it. In awards play for the below-the-line crafts, with Elordi a long shot for Best Supporting Actor."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Frankenstein on screen",
      "note": "Sean's canon of adaptations",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Frankenstein (1931)",
          "note": "James Whale's version: still taught, still scary, and it works on a seven-year-old."
        },
        {
          "title": "Bride of Frankenstein",
          "year": 1935,
          "note": "Whale's follow-up, cited alongside the original as the peak."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Curse of Frankenstein",
          "year": 1957,
          "note": "Sean's pick of the Hammer films; a new Warner Archive 4K is out."
        },
        {
          "title": "Flesh for Frankenstein",
          "year": 1973,
          "note": "Paul Morrissey's depraved double-revival take. Rob's a fan; del Toro's could have used its freak flag."
        },
        {
          "title": "Depraved",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Larry Fessenden's clever reimagining, with a revived U.S. soldier."
        },
        {
          "title": "Mary Shelley's Frankenstein",
          "year": 1994,
          "note": "Kenneth Branagh's operatic version, with De Niro as the monster. The unmade Frank Darabont script has a cult reputation; del Toro says reading it made him want to make his own."
        }
      ]
    },
